WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:07.007
♪

00:08.425 --> 00:10.385
EDWIN:
Thank you for finding my bike.

00:10.385 --> 00:12.513
It's too bad you didn't find
my money, officer.

00:12.513 --> 00:13.680
OFFICER:
Hmm.

00:14.097 --> 00:17.059
Well, normally we'd never
actually make a house call.

00:17.059 --> 00:18.060
EDWIN:
But you wanted to be sure

00:18.060 --> 00:19.353
I got this busted tire, right?

00:19.770 --> 00:23.232
But everybody at the precinct
heard about how you saved that dog.

00:23.232 --> 00:25.317
I really appreciate the effort. Yeah.

00:26.610 --> 00:28.737
Bye now.
[door closes]

00:29.446 --> 00:31.448
Well, we gotta go down south.

00:32.698 --> 00:34.284
Why would anyone go down south?

00:34.284 --> 00:36.495
'Cause I need to get a legit job, son.

00:36.495 --> 00:39.373
And I can't get that
without a Social Security card.

00:39.873 --> 00:41.750
And I can't get that
without a driver's license.

00:41.750 --> 00:44.962
And I can't get that
without a birth certificate.

00:46.547 --> 00:49.967
And my birth certificate
is in Union Springs, Alabama.

00:49.967 --> 00:51.802
That does not sound
like a place with 5G.

00:51.802 --> 00:54.805
It's not like any place
you've ever been, that's for sure.

00:57.641 --> 00:59.643
But you know what Richard Wright said?

01:00.644 --> 01:03.814
"I was not leaving the south
to forget the south,

01:03.814 --> 01:07.693
but so that someday
I might understand it."

01:07.693 --> 01:09.236
Am I supposed to know who that is?

01:09.236 --> 01:10.362
You're messing with me.

01:10.362 --> 01:11.947
He say that recently or something?

01:11.947 --> 01:12.990
EDWIN:
Let me ask you.

01:14.366 --> 01:15.617
Do you know who, uh,

01:17.369 --> 01:18.704
Bayard Rustin is?

01:19.121 --> 01:20.163
No.

01:20.163 --> 01:21.290
Fannie Lou Hamer?

01:21.290 --> 01:23.584
What about Amiri Baraka?

01:24.918 --> 01:25.752
Damn, Finn.

01:27.629 --> 01:29.131
What Black people do you know?

01:29.131 --> 01:30.465
Like Obama.

01:30.465 --> 01:31.967
[chuckles] Yeah.

01:31.967 --> 01:32.885
Zendaya.

01:33.927 --> 01:34.845
David Williams.

01:34.845 --> 01:36.471
Who the hell is David Williams?

01:36.471 --> 01:39.057
David Williams is a famous
<i>Magic: The Gathering</i> player

01:39.057 --> 01:40.726
who became a famous poker player.

01:42.352 --> 01:44.104
Damn public schools.

01:44.104 --> 01:45.314
<i>♪ See You Soon</i> by Akemi Fox playing ♪

01:45.314 --> 01:47.232
<i>♪ Can I see you soon? ♪</i>

01:48.025 --> 01:49.902
<i>♪ We are so in tune ♪</i>

01:50.527 --> 01:52.196
<i>♪ There's so much we can do ♪</i>

01:52.863 --> 01:55.240
Hey. Look here. We gotta go down south.

01:55.240 --> 01:58.202
No, we need to start
knocking on doors--

01:58.202 --> 01:59.411
Boundaries. Boundaries. I know.
PAIGE: Yes. Yes.

01:59.411 --> 02:00.621
I'm sorry. I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

02:00.621 --> 02:02.998
But since you're here,
can I ask you a question?

02:02.998 --> 02:04.208
Sure.

02:04.208 --> 02:07.336
Have you ever tried
being with a nice woman?

02:07.961 --> 02:09.505
Or were they all hot meanies?

02:09.505 --> 02:11.131
Don't knock a hot meanie, Paige.

02:12.007 --> 02:13.634
Why are you askin' me that?

02:13.634 --> 02:15.677
I'm just, I'm working on something.

02:17.638 --> 02:19.306
Why-why are we going down south?

02:19.306 --> 02:21.934
Because with my bike gone,
I need to get my birth certificate.

02:21.934 --> 02:23.393
Okay, I gotta ask you something.

02:23.393 --> 02:26.772
Are you aware that your son
doesn't know Black history?

02:27.314 --> 02:29.191
Might not even know he's Black.

02:29.191 --> 02:31.902
He knows he's Black.
This is South Minneapolis.

02:31.902 --> 02:34.530
When he walks out of this house,
his head is on swivel.

02:34.530 --> 02:36.031
Why do you need a birth certificate?

02:36.031 --> 02:37.282
Are you thinking about getting a real job?

02:37.282 --> 02:38.825
Because if you are,

02:38.825 --> 02:41.787
I would like to send
a gift basket to the bicycle thief.

02:41.787 --> 02:44.289
So it's your fault your son
doesn't know who Bayard Rustin was.

02:44.289 --> 02:47.292
- He-- He doesn't?
- He does not.

02:47.292 --> 02:49.461
Oh, that's fine. Identities are complex.

02:49.461 --> 02:51.672
There are a lot of
different kinds of ways to be Black.

02:51.672 --> 02:54.216
Your way is not more valid
than his way or my way.

02:54.216 --> 02:57.886
But I like this
whole down south adventure idea.

02:57.886 --> 02:59.263
I'm into it.
EDWIN: Good.

02:59.263 --> 03:01.306
'Cause y'all need some nigrescence.

03:01.306 --> 03:04.434
Um, what the fuck is nigrescence?

03:04.434 --> 03:06.854
♪

03:06.854 --> 03:09.398
<i>Okay, everybody,
so we are here in Alabama</i>

03:09.398 --> 03:11.525
<i>because my dad needs
some official paperwork</i>

03:11.525 --> 03:13.527
<i>so he can get a real job.
Woo-woo!</i>

03:13.527 --> 03:15.571
And so that my son
can get some nigrescence.

03:15.571 --> 03:16.405
What's nigrescence?

03:16.405 --> 03:19.241
<i>I had the same question, so I Googled it.</i>

03:19.241 --> 03:20.367
I told you what it was now.

03:20.367 --> 03:23.161
What you're hearing is
this man's frustration.

03:23.161 --> 03:24.955
Because even though my child and I

03:24.955 --> 03:27.499
have been Black people
our entire lives-- Yes, Finn?

03:27.499 --> 03:28.792
- FINN: <i>Yes.
- Yes.</i>

03:28.792 --> 03:30.210
<i>Apparently we are doing it wrong.</i>

03:30.669 --> 03:33.922
So, nigrescence
is the process of becoming Black

03:33.922 --> 03:37.426
or developing one's racial identity
as a Black person.

03:37.426 --> 03:39.011
I learned about that
from my celly Harold.

03:39.011 --> 03:40.053
Shout-out to Harold.

03:40.679 --> 03:42.055
<i>Yeah. Shout-out to Harold.</i>
FINN: <i>Shout-out to Harold.</i>

03:42.055 --> 03:44.516
Okay, so there's five stages
to nigrescence.

03:44.516 --> 03:47.060
The first is pre-encounter,

03:47.060 --> 03:48.562
<i>then encounter.</i>

03:48.562 --> 03:50.397
<i>Then it gets a little tricky
because you have--</i>

03:50.397 --> 03:53.025
Wait, hold up.
This is not a college lecture.

03:53.025 --> 03:54.318
- I know, but I'm--
- Ah, ah!

03:54.318 --> 03:56.570
We are talking about an experience.

03:56.570 --> 03:58.322
Right.
EDWIN: Not an idea.

03:58.322 --> 04:00.115
And are we gonna be
on our phones the whole time?

04:00.115 --> 04:01.200
That's kind of the plan.

04:01.200 --> 04:03.368
♪

04:03.368 --> 04:05.829
<i>♪ I saw her walking down Broadway ♪</i>

04:06.580 --> 04:08.248
EDWIN:
Paige, can you put that thing down

04:08.248 --> 04:10.000
for even just a minute, girl?

04:10.000 --> 04:13.962
I cannot, because this is
really important and amazing.

04:13.962 --> 04:17.466
And I wanna document it for us
and for all my followers.

04:17.466 --> 04:21.845
So, hi, guys. This is the house
that my dad grew up in.

04:21.845 --> 04:22.971
<i>It's not what I expected at all.</i>

04:22.971 --> 04:24.890
I don't know what it is you expected.

04:24.890 --> 04:27.434
Just, I didn't imagine this exactly.
[cell phone chimes]

04:28.018 --> 04:29.061
Oh, hell, no.

04:29.645 --> 04:30.562
Who's that?

04:31.355 --> 04:32.439
Cousin.

04:32.439 --> 04:33.649
You're not gonna answer?

04:33.649 --> 04:35.150
We came all the way down here.

04:35.150 --> 04:36.652
Boy's a pain in the ass. No.

04:37.528 --> 04:40.489
I wanna just--
I wanna take this in right here.

04:41.365 --> 04:44.535
You know how long it's been since I

04:46.203 --> 04:47.454
smell this air?

04:49.665 --> 04:51.166
- It smells like--
- Dial-up?

04:51.917 --> 04:53.961
Yeah, you wish you could have
grown up here, boy.

04:55.838 --> 04:59.883
Catching tadpoles,
balancing on the train tracks.

05:00.384 --> 05:04.221
It's a whole different type of freedom.

05:04.888 --> 05:06.890
If it was so great,
then why'd you leave?

05:06.890 --> 05:07.724
EDWIN:
Wasn't up to me.

05:07.724 --> 05:09.768
My mama came home one day and said,

05:10.978 --> 05:11.937
"Time to go."

05:14.773 --> 05:16.358
This place has been empty ever since,

05:18.026 --> 05:19.027
what, '66?

05:19.027 --> 05:20.612
That cannot be true.

05:21.280 --> 05:23.866
Who's trying to move
to Union Springs, Alabama, Paige?

05:24.449 --> 05:26.493
Actually, that could be true.
EDWIN: Hey.

05:27.369 --> 05:28.287
[grunts]

05:29.162 --> 05:31.164
Alright, let's go
find this birth certificate.

05:31.164 --> 05:33.375
PAIGE:
Well, don't we need a key?

05:33.375 --> 05:35.919
Nobody uses keys down here, Paige.

05:40.215 --> 05:43.260
I'll be in in a second.
I'm just at three percent.

05:43.260 --> 05:44.469
EDWIN:
Okay.

05:47.890 --> 05:50.267
♪

05:50.267 --> 05:51.894
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>Text from Mal.</i>

05:51.894 --> 05:53.937
<i>"I'm your boyfriend now
and a good boyfriend</i>

05:53.937 --> 05:57.399
<i>"tells you how he misses you
and sees how your trip is going.</i>

05:57.900 --> 06:00.736
<i>So how is it going? Kiss emoji."</i>

06:00.736 --> 06:02.070
<i>Do you want to reply?</i>

06:02.070 --> 06:03.906
I don't know.

06:03.906 --> 06:05.532
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>Sorry, I didn't get that.</i>

06:06.325 --> 06:09.578
I said I don't know because he is great.

06:09.578 --> 06:10.579
He's almost perfect.

06:10.579 --> 06:12.414
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>Sorry, I didn't get that.</i>

06:13.916 --> 06:17.252
I want to accept the love
of an emotionally available man

06:17.252 --> 06:18.462
who's interested in me.

06:20.172 --> 06:21.632
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>Sorry, I didn't get that.</i>

06:21.632 --> 06:23.509
<i>Do you want to reply?</i>

06:23.509 --> 06:24.968
Now you're just being rude.

06:24.968 --> 06:27.638
Just one bar, that's all I ask.

06:27.638 --> 06:29.556
You need to put that down
and come help, son.

06:29.556 --> 06:30.432
FINN:
Need to?

06:31.225 --> 06:33.143
My mom always gives me options.

06:33.143 --> 06:35.354
Yeah, well, your mama
was never on the streets.

06:35.354 --> 06:36.396
Just do what I say.

06:38.065 --> 06:40.734
Hey... look here.

06:43.487 --> 06:46.156
This is me right there. Yeah.

06:46.865 --> 06:47.783
Right there.

06:49.618 --> 06:50.911
Why are there no white people?

06:51.662 --> 06:54.665
'Cause the white people were
across town in the school with books.

06:55.332 --> 06:57.668
Yeah, segregation 101, Finn.

06:58.043 --> 07:00.671
Of course. I just didn't know
you were that old.

07:01.505 --> 07:02.923
That ain't that long ago.

07:03.757 --> 07:06.176
Just that all the pictures
they show you of segregation,

07:06.176 --> 07:07.594
in black and white.

07:07.594 --> 07:08.679
On purpose.

07:10.973 --> 07:12.850
Ah. Let me try that.

07:15.060 --> 07:19.022
Hey, this is like a field trip,
but interesting.

07:20.148 --> 07:22.484
You know, when I meet other Black kids,

07:22.484 --> 07:23.861
they don't always know.

07:24.570 --> 07:26.947
Like, it's just weird
to go up and be all like,

07:26.947 --> 07:29.032
hi, I, too, am Black.

07:29.658 --> 07:32.160
Don't say it like that, Finn.
That sounded kinda weird.

07:35.372 --> 07:37.499
I mean, it's facts, though,
you know, I just,

07:37.499 --> 07:40.627
I feel like I have to
prove that I'm Black.

07:40.627 --> 07:41.962
EDWIN:
Let me tell you something.

07:41.962 --> 07:44.298
Defending your Blackness
to other Black people?

07:46.091 --> 07:47.968
That's one of the Blackest things
you could do.

07:49.595 --> 07:51.305
Wasn't Martin Luther King around here?

07:51.305 --> 07:52.639
You ever go to a march?

07:52.639 --> 07:53.932
My mama always had to work.

07:57.603 --> 07:59.104
I remember when they killed him, though.

07:59.104 --> 08:00.355
Whoa.

08:00.355 --> 08:03.066
Yeah, man. The way that brother talked.

08:04.318 --> 08:07.779
You really believed you could have
all the things he said you could have.

08:07.779 --> 08:09.907
♪

08:09.907 --> 08:12.701
Then right when you starting to feel,

08:13.202 --> 08:16.455
yes, I can have these things,

08:17.539 --> 08:20.792
they shot him down in broad daylight.

08:22.336 --> 08:24.087
That fucked a lot of people up.

08:24.087 --> 08:26.465
♪

08:26.465 --> 08:27.591
Me included.

08:32.721 --> 08:37.726
♪

08:41.355 --> 08:43.941
Being in here is making my dad so real.

08:43.941 --> 08:47.319
Like, more real
than he even is in real life.

08:47.319 --> 08:48.987
If that's possible.

08:52.241 --> 08:53.450
Oh, my God.

08:54.201 --> 08:57.079
Okay, I think that this is his room.

08:57.871 --> 09:00.958
I mean, I think he slept here, right?

09:02.000 --> 09:05.087
Look at these tiny, tiny beds.

09:05.087 --> 09:07.297
[gasps] Oh, my God.

09:07.297 --> 09:10.008
Was my father ever this small?

09:12.177 --> 09:13.220
[sighs]

09:17.891 --> 09:19.434
BOY: [echoing]
<i>Mommy, I'm cold.</i>

09:19.434 --> 09:24.523
♪

09:24.523 --> 09:26.233
<i>I'm scared.</i>

09:26.233 --> 09:29.945
♪

09:29.945 --> 09:31.488
PAIGE:
What are you doing down there?

09:31.989 --> 09:32.948
Hiding.

09:32.948 --> 09:37.369
♪

09:37.369 --> 09:38.370
What's your name?

09:38.370 --> 09:40.163
Eddie Alexander.

09:41.915 --> 09:43.750
[softly] <i>Oh, God. Oh.</i>

09:45.043 --> 09:46.503
EDDIE:
I don't wanna go.

09:47.212 --> 09:48.046
Oh. [exhales]

09:52.092 --> 09:54.344
Hey. Uh, what is he doing?

09:54.344 --> 09:55.971
Messing with his phone again.

09:55.971 --> 09:58.265
Paige, I can't find
this birth certificate anywhere.

09:58.265 --> 10:00.976
Why-why-why-why did
Grandma Martha leave?

10:01.602 --> 10:03.270
I already told you, we just left.

10:03.270 --> 10:04.479
PAIGE:
No, but that doesn't make sense.

10:04.479 --> 10:06.732
And when something doesn't make sense,
it's because somebody's lying.

10:06.732 --> 10:08.692
That's what Judge Judy says.

10:08.692 --> 10:09.860
She loves Judge Judy.

10:09.860 --> 10:10.819
PAIGE:
I do.

10:11.486 --> 10:12.446
Ju--

10:12.946 --> 10:14.615
Paige, why would I lie to you?

10:14.615 --> 10:16.533
I don't know. You tell me.

10:20.204 --> 10:22.623
It's a long time ago
and I don't remember everything.

10:24.458 --> 10:27.336
<i>The sheriff and his brother,
they came to the house.</i>

10:29.880 --> 10:31.173
Daddy was away, preaching.

10:31.673 --> 10:33.509
♪

10:33.509 --> 10:35.302
<i>And mama was real upset.</i>

10:35.302 --> 10:37.095
They wanted to terrify my mother.

10:37.513 --> 10:38.347
[pounds on door]

10:38.972 --> 10:39.848
And they did.

10:40.432 --> 10:44.520
But the next thing I remember,
we moved to Birmingham.

10:44.520 --> 10:46.522
♪

10:46.522 --> 10:47.731
[sniffles]

10:48.273 --> 10:49.233
And that's it?

10:49.233 --> 10:50.108
That's it.

10:51.902 --> 10:55.781
And I thought you wanted to help me
find this birth certificate, girl.

10:56.365 --> 10:59.576
So, look, that church I told you about?

11:00.202 --> 11:01.286
We gotta go there.

11:02.246 --> 11:03.288
Come on.

11:04.081 --> 11:05.791
PAIGE:
Come on. They might have Wi-Fi.

11:05.791 --> 11:06.834
Stop.

11:06.834 --> 11:08.210
PAIGE:
But probably not.

11:08.210 --> 11:09.044
What?

11:09.044 --> 11:11.463
♪

11:11.463 --> 11:13.090
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>Text from Mal.</i>

11:13.090 --> 11:15.634
<i>"Hey, baby, you're not
replying to my texts, so--"</i>

11:15.634 --> 11:17.135
That boy is so sprung.

11:17.135 --> 11:18.971
Low-key. It's pretty hilarious.

11:19.680 --> 11:20.806
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>"Guess I'll have to tell you</i>

11:20.806 --> 11:23.100
<i>what I'm planning to do to you
when you get back."</i>

11:23.100 --> 11:24.977
Oh. No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.

11:24.977 --> 11:27.104
AUTOMATED VOICE:
<i>I want to pull your panties to the side--</i>

11:27.104 --> 11:29.189
- Oh, my God! Mom!
- Okay! Thank you. No, no, no!

11:29.189 --> 11:32.317
No, sorry, sorry. I'm sorry.
I'm sorry! I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

11:32.317 --> 11:36.280
♪

11:39.366 --> 11:40.492
Sister Annie?

11:43.036 --> 11:44.413
Oh, good afternoon.

11:45.330 --> 11:46.456
Can I help you?

11:46.456 --> 11:49.126
I don't know if you remember me. Um--

11:49.793 --> 11:52.796
Uh, my name is Edwin, and my family and I,

11:52.796 --> 11:55.924
we-we lived around here
a long, long time ago.

11:56.341 --> 11:57.801
The Alexander boy?
EDWIN: Oh, my God.

11:57.801 --> 11:59.553
Yes, ma'am! [laughs]

12:00.971 --> 12:02.472
- Yes, ma'am.
- Well, I'll be.

12:03.265 --> 12:05.184
- It is you.
- Yes.

12:06.393 --> 12:07.811
It's good to see you.

12:08.937 --> 12:10.939
- Is this your wife?
- Oh, no, no, no, no.

12:11.356 --> 12:14.067
This is my daughter and my grandson.

12:14.067 --> 12:15.485
ANNIE:
Where'd the time go?

12:15.485 --> 12:18.238
Oh, I ask myself that every day.

12:18.238 --> 12:21.200
If I'd known y'all were coming,
I'd have made some Folgers.

12:21.200 --> 12:23.202
EDWIN:
Oh, no, no, no. We're good. We're good.

12:23.869 --> 12:27.539
Um, but there is something
I was hoping you could help me with.

12:28.248 --> 12:32.794
Is there any chance at all
that you have my baptism records?

12:32.794 --> 12:35.547
Well, now, that's going a long way back.

12:35.547 --> 12:36.715
EDWIN:
I know.

12:36.715 --> 12:37.841
But we can look.

12:40.552 --> 12:43.555
You know, that flood
took everything from us back then.

12:43.555 --> 12:46.016
But if I have it, it's in there.

12:47.184 --> 12:48.143
Thank you, ma'am.

12:51.146 --> 12:52.231
Come here, you.

12:52.231 --> 12:53.315
Yeah.

12:54.358 --> 12:55.526
Look at you.

12:55.526 --> 12:58.028
Oh, my. You're so handsome.

12:58.028 --> 12:59.279
Oh, thanks.

12:59.279 --> 13:00.447
You want some Folgers?

13:01.073 --> 13:03.033
I'm okay. Thank you.

13:03.659 --> 13:07.663
Um, Miss Annie, can I ask you
just a couple of questions.

13:07.663 --> 13:08.997
EDWIN:
Don't bother the lady now, Paige.

13:11.250 --> 13:13.252
- PAIGE: Um--
- What do you wanna know, baby?

13:13.252 --> 13:15.420
I just wanna know what happened.

13:15.420 --> 13:18.715
You know, why-why did
Grandma Martha leave Alabama?

13:18.715 --> 13:21.260
I tried to ask my dad,
but he doesn't remember.

13:21.260 --> 13:24.179
What? Of course, he remembers.

13:24.179 --> 13:25.597
He saw everything.

13:27.182 --> 13:28.100
What do you mean?

13:28.767 --> 13:30.018
Back then, honey,

13:31.603 --> 13:34.523
the sheriff would come up
in the middle of the night,

13:34.523 --> 13:36.733
lights off and everything.

13:36.733 --> 13:38.777
♪

13:38.777 --> 13:40.070
[indistinct yelling]

13:40.779 --> 13:43.740
<i>And they dragged that poor woman
out of the house...</i>

13:43.740 --> 13:46.034
- [indistinct shouting]
- No! No!

13:46.034 --> 13:47.953
ANNIE:
<i>...in front of all the kids.</i>

13:48.662 --> 13:51.456
<i>The next morning when Martha came back,</i>

13:51.957 --> 13:55.294
<i>she was limping and full of bruises.</i>

13:58.881 --> 14:01.383
The whole family left that very day.

14:04.887 --> 14:06.054
Is that true?

14:09.433 --> 14:11.476
It's not here.
[drawer closes]

14:11.977 --> 14:12.895
I'm hungry.

14:14.730 --> 14:16.148
Anybody else hungry?

14:20.319 --> 14:21.236
Thank you.

14:22.070 --> 14:23.780
Sister Annie, I appreciate it.

14:26.783 --> 14:30.245
♪

14:31.246 --> 14:36.418
♪

14:39.671 --> 14:40.672
FINN:

14:41.590 --> 14:42.591
Mm!

14:44.009 --> 14:46.136
Bro, this soul food is the juice.

14:46.136 --> 14:47.429
Why doesn't yours taste so good?

14:47.429 --> 14:48.472
What?

14:48.472 --> 14:49.348
It's true.

14:51.266 --> 14:53.810
Maybe because I was
raised by Scandinavians,

14:53.810 --> 14:55.979
and they care more about pickled herring.

14:56.522 --> 14:58.398
Well, this is all I wanna eat
for the rest of my life.

14:58.398 --> 15:01.860
<i>♪ These Ain't Raindrops</i>
by James Carr playing ♪

15:01.860 --> 15:03.320
♪

15:03.320 --> 15:06.073
<i>♪ Just one kiss would do so much ♪</i>

15:06.073 --> 15:09.451
<i>♪ It would drive away all my fears ♪</i>

15:10.327 --> 15:12.287
<i>♪ These ain't raindrops ♪</i>

15:12.287 --> 15:15.123
So we gonna talk at all

15:15.123 --> 15:17.292
about what happened with Deacon Annie?

15:18.335 --> 15:19.503
What is there to talk about?

15:19.503 --> 15:23.924
If you keep pretending
that you have no traumas,

15:23.924 --> 15:26.426
they are gonna
keep coming out sideways.

15:26.426 --> 15:28.220
Ancient history, Paige.

15:28.220 --> 15:29.596
PAIGE:
History maybe.

15:29.596 --> 15:32.391
But perhaps part of why
you don't wanna talk about it

15:32.391 --> 15:36.645
is because that was the first domino
that led you to prison.

15:37.396 --> 15:39.356
- You doing therapy on me, girl?
- Me?

15:39.356 --> 15:40.732
And I'm not even convinced

15:40.732 --> 15:42.568
that that shit works with white folk,
and here you come.

15:42.568 --> 15:43.569
No, it works.

15:43.569 --> 15:46.280
It works for white folks.
It also works for us.

15:46.280 --> 15:47.823
Everybody needs therapy.

15:47.823 --> 15:50.117
- If therapy was so great...
- Yeah.

15:50.117 --> 15:53.120
...you wouldn't be asking me
if I ever fell in love with a nice woman.

15:53.745 --> 15:55.873
You're worried about yourself, Paige.

15:55.873 --> 15:58.125
No, I'm not worried.

15:58.125 --> 16:00.294
I just don't like hot meanies.

16:00.294 --> 16:02.963
And you don't like a nice guy either.

16:02.963 --> 16:04.506
'Cause if you were,

16:05.465 --> 16:07.885
Mal Kennedy would not be texting me

16:09.136 --> 16:10.137
looking for you.

16:10.971 --> 16:13.182
Oh, but what do I know?

16:13.182 --> 16:14.266
You're the professional.

16:18.187 --> 16:19.813
So can I have your cornbread?

16:22.482 --> 16:24.568
Oh, my. Yes. Thank you.

16:26.778 --> 16:27.654
Oh, damn it.

16:27.654 --> 16:28.822
MAN:
Oh, here you go, buddy.

16:31.909 --> 16:33.160
Thank you.

16:33.160 --> 16:34.328
I'm happy you're cleaning up.

16:35.162 --> 16:36.330
Not like them moon crickets.

16:38.373 --> 16:39.666
Moon crickets?

16:40.292 --> 16:41.460
Probably before your time.

16:42.753 --> 16:43.879
Never mind, kid.

16:45.297 --> 16:46.340
You have a good one, huh?

16:48.800 --> 16:51.386
Look, Bumpy,
we just finished lunch, but, uh,

16:52.221 --> 16:53.680
I still got this other thing.

16:54.139 --> 16:55.849
I may have to see you next trip.

16:56.558 --> 16:57.518
Yep.

16:57.518 --> 16:59.811
Hey, Mal, I am really sorry

16:59.811 --> 17:02.356
that it's taken me so long
to get back to you.

17:02.356 --> 17:04.858
This trip with my dad is a lot.

17:06.068 --> 17:09.363
I'm just watching him
try to avoid all his trauma.

17:10.739 --> 17:13.283
It's like he thinks the past
is actually in the past, you know.

17:13.283 --> 17:14.993
And you and I know
that it doesn't work that way.

17:14.993 --> 17:18.372
That shit happens
and you shut down a little bit here

17:18.372 --> 17:19.706
and you shut down a little bit there,

17:19.706 --> 17:21.375
but the trauma doesn't go anywhere, right?

17:21.375 --> 17:22.709
And then before you know it,
you're grown up

17:22.709 --> 17:24.545
and you've passed your trauma down.

17:24.545 --> 17:29.174
Just like my dad gave me
his weird knuckles and his ashy skin.

17:31.593 --> 17:33.929
[indistinct chatter]
[Paige sighs]

17:33.929 --> 17:35.347
Oh, shit.

17:35.764 --> 17:39.309
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.
Oh, my God. I think, um--

17:40.727 --> 17:42.312
I think that he might be right.

17:42.312 --> 17:47.359
I think that maybe I am
a little bit worried about myself, and I--

17:48.193 --> 17:49.820
Oh, God, I don't even know
why I'm still talking

17:49.820 --> 17:51.446
because I'm definitely gonna delete this.

17:51.446 --> 17:52.823
Although maybe I shouldn't.

17:52.823 --> 17:55.158
I probably will.
But I don't know. Maybe I won't.

17:55.158 --> 17:57.202
I-I think I shouldn't decide right now.

17:57.202 --> 17:59.162
I think I should decide later.
Okay. Thank you. Bye.

18:02.165 --> 18:03.417
You reach Mal?

18:03.417 --> 18:05.294
Uh, no. But you know what?

18:05.294 --> 18:06.837
I just had a really big breakthrough,

18:06.837 --> 18:08.547
so I think I'm going to
at some point, eventually.

18:09.256 --> 18:10.632
Therapy sounds real helpful.

18:11.508 --> 18:15.637
Um, I think we should go
to the courthouse. You ready?

18:15.637 --> 18:16.763
Not really.

18:20.100 --> 18:22.311
This place has got bad vibes, man.

18:23.437 --> 18:26.190
Maybe it's bringing up something deeper.

18:27.649 --> 18:30.569
Yeah, I got no time
for something deeper right now, baby.

18:31.612 --> 18:33.030
I think this is, uh--

18:34.573 --> 18:35.574
Good luck in there.

18:36.658 --> 18:37.576
Yeah.

18:39.286 --> 18:40.746
- Come with me.
- Okay.

18:40.746 --> 18:42.915
PAIGE:
<i>Grandma Martha was a maid,</i>

18:42.915 --> 18:45.334
and she was accused of stealing jewelry.

18:46.210 --> 18:47.461
Who are the Vickers?

18:48.212 --> 18:51.131
Uh, I think just some
white people she worked for.

18:52.341 --> 18:53.884
She didn't do it, did she?

18:56.762 --> 18:59.306
I don't know. Um, I hope not.

19:00.140 --> 19:05.270
Excuse me. What does it mean
that they "stayed sentencing"?

19:06.063 --> 19:09.233
That usually happens when
the prosecutors know that it was bullshit.

19:09.816 --> 19:13.737
And based on that date,
you know, the type of time they were on.

19:14.321 --> 19:16.448
You're saying
they dragged her out of her house

19:16.448 --> 19:19.117
in the middle of the night
on a fake charge

19:20.410 --> 19:22.621
and then beat her in front of her kids?

19:23.622 --> 19:25.457
You want me to make you a copy?

19:25.457 --> 19:26.583
No.

19:27.709 --> 19:29.127
Thank you. Um--

19:30.879 --> 19:33.006
I wouldn't wanna remember that either.

19:33.006 --> 19:33.924
Come on.

19:33.924 --> 19:38.178
♪

19:38.178 --> 19:39.888
Hey.
PAIGE: Hey.

19:39.888 --> 19:41.098
EDWIN:
They found me.

19:41.098 --> 19:42.891
- They did?
- [laughs] Yeah, they did.

19:42.891 --> 19:44.268
[laughter]

19:44.268 --> 19:45.686
Wow!

19:45.686 --> 19:46.854
We might make our flight.

19:46.854 --> 19:48.063
[laughter]

19:48.063 --> 19:49.356
EDWIN:
Thank you, Jesus.

19:49.356 --> 19:53.026
Oh, wow. It says here
that your actual name is Eddie.

19:53.026 --> 19:54.236
Eddie?
EDWIN: Oh.

19:54.236 --> 19:55.487
When did that happen?

19:55.487 --> 19:57.197
Wh-- Why didn't I know that?

19:57.197 --> 19:58.532
I changed it, Paige.

20:00.617 --> 20:03.245
I wanted a name
with some dignity and respect.

20:03.245 --> 20:05.789
Not the name of a scared little boy.

20:06.874 --> 20:09.001
- What's a moon cricket?
- No clue.

20:09.001 --> 20:13.255
Uh, wow,
that's one of them OG slurs, man.

20:14.423 --> 20:17.426
Back in the day, they used to say
that the slaves sang at night

20:18.051 --> 20:19.678
like moon crickets.

20:22.681 --> 20:24.266
Why is that funny?

20:24.266 --> 20:26.894
You gotta laugh
to keep from crying, girl.

20:26.894 --> 20:28.854
Some guy
at the barbecue place called us that.

20:28.854 --> 20:32.316
What? That's awful.
I'm so sorry that happened.

20:32.316 --> 20:35.027
Wait now. That may not be a bad thing.

20:35.027 --> 20:39.823
My grandson just said
they called <i>us</i> moon crickets.

20:39.823 --> 20:42.951
Which means the nigrescence is working.

20:43.744 --> 20:46.705
Hey, you a Black man, son.
Come on over here.

20:46.705 --> 20:48.498
Shit, I guess.
EDWIN: Ahh!

20:48.498 --> 20:51.126
[grunting]

20:51.126 --> 20:52.294
Ha!

20:54.463 --> 20:57.758
Okay. All I need from you
is ten dollars,

20:57.758 --> 20:59.760
your signature and some ID.

21:00.928 --> 21:02.638
Now, that's a, here's $20.

21:03.055 --> 21:03.972
- CLERK: Great.
- Um--

21:04.640 --> 21:05.766
I don't have the ID,

21:05.766 --> 21:09.436
but I do have a letter
from my parole officer,

21:10.312 --> 21:13.899
and it says that I am, uh,

21:15.442 --> 21:16.568
who I say I am.

21:19.112 --> 21:23.075
Well, unfortunately
in this township in Alabama,

21:23.075 --> 21:26.995
I can't... release this without photo ID.

21:27.871 --> 21:30.290
Uh, it was good enough
to get on the plane.

21:30.290 --> 21:32.167
I mean, but it's not
good enough for y'all?

21:32.167 --> 21:34.294
I mean, come on, man. Come on.
There must be something you can do.

21:34.294 --> 21:36.380
Sorry, there is a lot of identity theft
going around.

21:36.380 --> 21:38.924
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa,
I'm not an identity thief.

21:39.424 --> 21:41.343
I am me, it says it right here.

21:41.343 --> 21:44.805
This is my, this is my daughter
and this is my grandson.

21:44.805 --> 21:46.723
Sir, you need to calm down.
EDWIN: I'm calm.

21:46.723 --> 21:49.601
I need the birth certificate
to get the ID

21:49.601 --> 21:51.937
so I can fix my daughter's roof.

21:51.937 --> 21:53.689
- Come on, man.
- Sir. Sir.

21:53.689 --> 21:55.482
I need you to come back
when you get the ID,

21:55.482 --> 21:56.358
there are signs everywhere.

21:56.358 --> 21:57.609
Here's the deal, Eddie.

21:57.609 --> 22:00.153
Oh, stop. My name is Edwin Alexander.

22:00.153 --> 22:01.780
Okay? And you need to have some respect!

22:01.780 --> 22:03.031
CLERK:
I am trying to help you.

22:03.031 --> 22:04.658
- You ain't done shit for me!
- Please. Please.

22:04.658 --> 22:06.326
CLERK:
Mr. Alexander, I'm trying to help you out.

22:06.326 --> 22:07.160
PAIGE:
Thank you.

22:07.953 --> 22:09.663
Paige, I don't know what else to do.

22:11.623 --> 22:13.333
I mean, why they let me out
if they go--

22:13.333 --> 22:15.210
if they gonna do me like this?

22:16.003 --> 22:17.254
And I'm trying to help you.

22:17.254 --> 22:19.840
I don't want you to worry
about my roof.

22:19.840 --> 22:23.552
Baby, it's my job
to worry about the roof!

22:24.303 --> 22:25.804
And these motherfuckers,

22:25.804 --> 22:28.682
they gonna block me,
they gonna block me,

22:28.682 --> 22:31.143
they gonna block me every time.

22:31.685 --> 22:33.520
[Edwin crying]

22:33.520 --> 22:38.775
♪

22:47.784 --> 22:52.080
No, it is not fair
that you don't get to help me,

22:53.749 --> 22:56.043
[voice breaking]
<i>but I'm okay.</i>

22:56.543 --> 23:00.214
<i>We're okay because we're safe.</i>

23:01.757 --> 23:05.761
<i>We don't have to run away
in the middle of the night</i>

23:05.761 --> 23:07.846
<i>to escape the things that scare us.</i>

23:07.846 --> 23:09.681
♪

23:09.681 --> 23:12.226
That stops here with us.

23:12.226 --> 23:15.562
♪

23:15.562 --> 23:17.648
I don't trust that therapy shit
but I trust you.

23:23.195 --> 23:24.321
I trust you.

23:32.996 --> 23:34.373
PAIGE:
<i>Let's go catch our flight.</i>

23:35.499 --> 23:37.125
Oh. Paige.

23:37.543 --> 23:38.585
PAIGE:
Yeah.

23:38.585 --> 23:41.171
I told Cousin Bumpy
we'd be stopping by real quick.

23:42.214 --> 23:45.133
Baby, it's been 20 years.
I should at least go see the man.

23:45.133 --> 23:48.303
I have my TED Talk tomorrow
and Finn has school.

23:48.303 --> 23:50.305
- I can miss school.
- No, you cannot.

23:51.598 --> 23:54.893
But you should go. You should stay.

23:54.893 --> 23:56.770
You know, it's cool. I trust you.

23:56.770 --> 24:00.732
And... I think you need
to see your cousin Bumpy.

24:00.732 --> 24:02.693
Promise I'll get
the first thing smokin' tomorrow.

24:03.235 --> 24:04.444
I know you will.

24:05.487 --> 24:06.446
Alright, Paige.

24:07.322 --> 24:09.199
Everything I've ever done is for you.

24:11.034 --> 24:12.035
Right or wrong.

24:13.245 --> 24:14.496
I just hope you know that.

24:16.456 --> 24:18.792
Yeah, I think I'm starting to see that.

24:21.670 --> 24:23.922
Also, I'm gonna text Mal.

24:23.922 --> 24:24.756
EDWIN:
Oh.

24:24.756 --> 24:28.135
Because I think that one of us
should try to be with someone nice.

24:28.886 --> 24:30.179
You're right about that.

24:30.179 --> 24:31.388
[Paige chuckles]

24:34.433 --> 24:35.976
Can we bring soul food on the plane?

24:37.019 --> 24:38.145
Yes.

24:38.145 --> 24:39.354
Sick.

24:39.354 --> 24:41.106
Nigrescence at work.

24:41.773 --> 24:43.483
Get the man some soul food.

24:43.901 --> 24:46.486
Would you like a side order
of hypertension?

24:46.486 --> 24:47.487
FINN:
Can I still get soul food?

24:47.487 --> 24:51.700
♪

24:51.700 --> 24:52.659
[kisses]

